So I can do rmdir Documents.

248
00:11:06,330 --> 00:11:10,080
And now, if I do ls,
it doesn't exist.

249
00:11:10,080 --> 00:11:12,300
Now, importantly,
though, that only

250
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:15,340
works if you have
nothing in that folder.

251
00:11:15,340 --> 00:11:17,570
So let's, for a
second, say I do mkdir.

252
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:22,060
That exists again.

253
00:11:22,060 --> 00:11:23,520
And now, let's say
I want to create

254
00:11:23,520 --> 00:11:26,250
a folder in that directory.

255
00:11:26,250 --> 00:11:29,370
So I'll go cd Documents.

256
00:11:29,370 --> 00:11:33,730
And then from here, if I want to
create a file, all I have to do

257
00:11:33,730 --> 00:11:36,510
or one way I can do this
is to just type touch.

258
00:11:36,510 --> 00:11:39,420
So touch basically
creates a file

259
00:11:39,420 --> 00:11:42,550
or updates the
timestamp of that file.

260
00:11:42,550 --> 00:11:46,980
It's kind of the idea of saying
like, hey, I want to create

261
00:11:46,980 --> 00:11:49,470
a file on my computer.

262
00:11:49,470 --> 00:11:50,650
I'm touching it.

263
00:11:50,650 --> 00:11:52,930
And if it doesn't exist,
that makes it exist.

264
00:11:52,930 --> 00:11:55,410
If it does exist,
then it's going

265
00:11:55,410 --> 00:11:59,250
to just say, hey, somebody
just interacted with that file

266
00:11:59,250 --> 00:12:00,930
recently.

267
00:12:00,930 --> 00:12:04,590
So I'm going to
call it test.txt.

268
00:12:04,590 --> 00:12:08,580
I'm just making a folder or
making a file called test.txt.

269
00:12:08,580 --> 00:12:12,490
So you can see there, now that
shows up in my Documents folder

270
00:12:12,490 --> 00:12:15,150
right when I do ls.

271
00:12:15,150 --> 00:12:23,160
But if I go back one directory
and do rmdir Documents,

272
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:25,890
notice that it says, fail to
remove directory documents

273
00:12:25,890 --> 00:12:27,270
or directory not empty.

274
00:12:27,270 --> 00:12:30,310
So you can't delete directories
that have information in them.

275
00:12:30,310 --> 00:12:32,550
There is a way to do that
to basically recursively

276
00:12:32,550 --> 00:12:34,657
delete everything in
there, and I'll show you

277
00:12:34,657 --> 00:12:35,740
how to do that eventually.

278
00:12:35,740 --> 00:12:39,197
But it's not something
you want to do every two

279
00:12:39,197 --> 00:12:41,530
seconds because you risk just
deleting a bunch of stuff.

280
00:12:41,530 --> 00:12:43,240
So it's good.

281
00:12:43,240 --> 00:12:44,740
It's important, or
better statement,

282
00:12:44,740 --> 00:12:47,485
it's best practice to
remove irrelevant files.

283
00:12:47,485 --> 00:12:49,860
And then if you get to the
point that you're completely--

284
00:12:49,860 --> 00:12:52,230
if it's a completely
empty directory, then

285
00:12:52,230 --> 00:12:55,560
certainly you can just remove
the directory with that.

286
00:12:55,560 --> 00:12:57,600
Also, I'll say that
I'm not expecting you

287
00:12:57,600 --> 00:12:59,110
to memorize all these commands.

288
00:12:59,110 --> 00:13:01,068
I have a cheat sheet here
that I'm referencing.

289
00:13:01,068 --> 00:13:03,110
I'm going to share this
cheat sheet with you guys

290
00:13:03,110 --> 00:13:03,670
as well, too.

291
00:13:03,670 --> 00:13:06,630
So there's no secret to these.

292
00:13:06,630 --> 00:13:08,520
And by all means,
as well, you'll

293
00:13:08,520 --> 00:13:10,920
find there's a set of commands
that typically you'll use

294
00:13:10,920 --> 00:13:12,730
and you'll memorize yourself.

295
00:13:12,730 --> 00:13:16,680
So not that critical for you
to stress about that right now.

296
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:19,230
But anyway, touch
creates the file.

297
00:13:19,230 --> 00:13:22,620
Now, as you know, though,
we didn't actually

298
00:13:22,620 --> 00:13:23,990
put anything in that file.

299
00:13:23,990 --> 00:13:25,910
We just said, let's
make it exist.

300
00:13:25,910 --> 00:13:29,270
I mean, if we did ls
dash l in this directory,

301
00:13:29,270 --> 00:13:32,420
you'd see that the size of this
file is zero kilobytes, right?

302
00:13:32,420 --> 00:13:34,760
There's literally no
information in there.

303
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:36,640
Not a very useful file.

304
00:13:36,640 --> 00:13:39,020
So the question is,
how do we edit a file?

305
00:13:39,020 --> 00:13:42,610
How do we make or add
information to that?

306
00:13:42,610 --> 00:13:44,810
So there are a couple
of ways we can do that.

307
00:13:44,810 --> 00:13:46,480
And basically, all
of them are just

308
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:49,100
variations of
different text editors.

309
00:13:49,100 --> 00:13:51,560
You can think about it like
opening Microsoft Word.

310
00:13:51,560 --> 00:13:55,382
It's just that it is a
little bit simpler than that.

311
00:13:55,382 --> 00:13:56,840
And that's a strength
as well, too.

312
00:13:56,840 --> 00:13:58,510
That means that it doesn't
take eight years to load,

313
00:13:58,510 --> 00:13:59,950
and it doesn't have all
these crazy features

314
00:13:59,950 --> 00:14:00,800
that you don't need.

315
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:02,570
It's just to edit text.

316
00:14:02,570 --> 00:14:05,860
So I'll do quite a bit, if
not all, of our programming

317
00:14:05,860 --> 00:14:09,340
in this course in
just this environment.

318
00:14:09,340 --> 00:14:12,610
One text editor that you
can use is called Nano.

319
00:14:12,610 --> 00:14:15,318
So if you just type nano and
then your file name-- if it

320
00:14:15,318 --> 00:14:16,610
doesn't exist, it'll create it.

321
00:14:16,610 --> 00:14:19,060
If it does exist,
you'll just edit it.

322
00:14:19,060 --> 00:14:21,640
Then it pops you into
this new fun window here.

323
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:28,090
And here I can just say
Sharad is editing this file.

324
00:14:28,090 --> 00:14:30,040
And you'll see
below here, there's

325
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:33,537
a bunch of things you can do.

326
00:14:33,537 --> 00:14:35,620
There are a bunch of options
that you can interact

327
00:14:35,620 --> 00:14:37,460
with here on these files.

328
00:14:37,460 --> 00:14:40,930
So if I do Command or
Control, depending on --

329
00:14:40,930 --> 00:14:43,222
if you're on Mac, it's
going to be Command.

330
00:14:43,222 --> 00:14:44,680
And if you're on
Windows, I believe

331
00:14:44,680 --> 00:14:46,630
it's going to be Control.

332
00:14:46,630 --> 00:14:49,540
But Control-X-- or
actually no, wrong.

333
00:14:49,540 --> 00:14:51,190
It's Control on both of them.

334
00:14:51,190 --> 00:14:56,480
Control-X and then Y. That was--
and actually, I'll do this again

335
00:14:56,480 --> 00:14:57,380
so you can see here.

336
00:14:57,380 --> 00:14:59,690
So unfortunately, you
can't see my keyboard,

337
00:14:59,690 --> 00:15:01,400
but I'm running this command.

338
00:15:01,400 --> 00:15:06,130
So Control-X. Then I'm
typing Y, because it asks me

339
00:15:06,130 --> 00:15:10,010
yes or no, do I want to save
this file or just x out of it?

340
00:15:10,010 --> 00:15:12,310
And then it's asking me the
file name to write it to,

341
00:15:12,310 --> 00:15:14,910
and then I just hit Enter.

342
00:15:14,910 --> 00:15:18,030
And so that now
has edited my file.

343
00:15:18,030 --> 00:15:21,610
One way I can check that
is to use the cat command.

344
00:15:21,610 --> 00:15:27,070
So cat will just print out all
of the contents of the file.

345
00:15:27,070 --> 00:15:29,830
And so you can see Sharad
is editing this file.

346
00:15:29,830 --> 00:15:32,740
So Nano is one
editor you can use.

347
00:15:32,740 --> 00:15:35,170
vim is another editor.

348
00:15:35,170 --> 00:15:37,700
Again, use whatever you're
most comfortable with.

349
00:15:37,700 --> 00:15:39,670
Looks different,
but functionally

350
00:15:39,670 --> 00:15:42,050
does the same thing,
except with this one.

351
00:15:42,050 --> 00:15:45,550
If you want to edit a
file, you type I first

352
00:15:45,550 --> 00:15:46,970
to put it in insert mode.

353
00:15:46,970 --> 00:15:49,180
You'll see it's now at
the bottom in insert mode.

354
00:15:49,180 --> 00:15:52,930
And then I can go
and make changes.

355
00:15:52,930 --> 00:15:55,420
So I'll go to the end of this.

356
00:15:55,420 --> 00:16:01,060
He did this part using Vim.

357
00:16:01,060 --> 00:16:04,040
And now if I want to
save and exit this file,

358
00:16:04,040 --> 00:16:08,110
I type Escape and
then Shift-Colon.

359
00:16:08,110 --> 00:16:10,300
And you'll see it put a
little colon down here.

360
00:16:10,300 --> 00:16:13,960
And then wq is to save and quit.

361
00:16:13,960 --> 00:16:15,500
Q would just be to quit.

362
00:16:15,500 --> 00:16:19,810
So there are an infinite
number of things

363
00:16:19,810 --> 00:16:22,090
you can do within
Nano, Vim, or whatever

364
00:16:22,090 --> 00:16:24,040
text editor you choose to use.

365
00:16:24,040 --> 00:16:26,180
I'm not by any means picky.

366
00:16:26,180 --> 00:16:28,370
Whatever works best
for you, you use it,

367
00:16:28,370 --> 00:16:30,020
but it's really,
really important

368
00:16:30,020 --> 00:16:32,070
to know how to
edit files on here.

369
00:16:32,070 --> 00:16:36,060
So try Nano, try Vim, Google it.

370
00:16:36,060 --> 00:16:39,500
You'll find infinite, again,
solutions or tips and tricks

371
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:41,252
on doing that.

372
00:16:41,252 --> 00:16:42,710
Here's two new ones
that I actually

373
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:46,010
hadn't ever used before,
but found recently.

374
00:16:46,010 --> 00:16:50,850
More prints out the displays,
the contents of the file,

375
00:16:50,850 --> 00:16:52,410
but it does it page by page.

376
00:16:52,410 --> 00:16:55,340
So we only had one page--
or, yeah, one short line

377
00:16:55,340 --> 00:16:57,020
in this file.

378
00:16:57,020 --> 00:17:01,940
But if you had a bunch of pages,
if you did cat in your file,

379
00:17:01,940 --> 00:17:03,860
it would dump out all
of them onto the screen.

380
00:17:03,860 --> 00:17:05,510
And it might overwhelm
your computer

381
00:17:05,510 --> 00:17:07,140
because you have so
much text in there.

382
00:17:07,140 --> 00:17:08,970
More does it page by page.

383
00:17:08,970 --> 00:17:10,970
So it's a good one
to use, and you just

384
00:17:10,970 --> 00:17:13,380
use the Spacebar to kind of
move along through the file.

385
00:17:13,380 --> 00:17:16,645
So a couple different ways to
view the contents of those.

386
00:17:19,490 --> 00:17:23,460
Next, I wanted to show you how
to move and copy files around.

387
00:17:23,460 --> 00:17:24,630
Really simple.

388
00:17:24,630 --> 00:17:28,520
But to show that, let's actually
create another directory here.

389
00:17:28,520 --> 00:17:29,940
So I'm going to
make a directory.

390
00:17:29,940 --> 00:17:31,523
Where are my documents
folder already?

391
00:17:31,523 --> 00:17:36,300
So let's call it, I
don't know, Contracts.

392
00:17:36,300 --> 00:17:39,180
Maybe I have a folder filled
with contracts in them.

393
00:17:39,180 --> 00:17:39,680
Right?

394
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:44,270
So I have my test.txt file,
and I have my Contracts folder.

395
00:17:44,270 --> 00:17:46,850
Let's say I want
to put my Contracts

396
00:17:46,850 --> 00:17:51,420
folder into my-- or my test
file into my Contracts folder.

397
00:17:51,420 --> 00:17:54,650
Well then I'll use
the mv command.

398
00:17:54,650 --> 00:18:01,160
I'll do test.txt, and
then I'll do Contracts.

399
00:18:01,160 --> 00:18:02,970
And actually, I'll show
you something here.

400
00:18:02,970 --> 00:18:05,240
I can also rename the
file in this point.

401
00:18:05,240 --> 00:18:06,590
So I can do test2,txt.

402
00:18:09,170 --> 00:18:14,220
And now, if I ls, I don't have
any file in my Documents folder.

403
00:18:14,220 --> 00:18:20,720
But if I go to my Contracts,
I have the test2.txt.

404
00:18:20,720 --> 00:18:24,270
So Move is often used
just to rename files, too.

405
00:18:24,270 --> 00:18:26,930
So for example, if I want
to just rename this file,

406
00:18:26,930 --> 00:18:29,340
I can leave it in
the same exact place.

407
00:18:29,340 --> 00:18:35,150
So I'll do test2.txt, and
I'll move it to test3.txt.

408
00:18:35,150 --> 00:18:39,500
So basically, what I'm saying
is move this file from here to--

409
00:18:39,500 --> 00:18:43,580
or from test2.txt in this
directory to test3.txt.

410
00:18:43,580 --> 00:18:47,300
It's the equivalent of
just renaming the file.

411
00:18:47,300 --> 00:18:50,160
Another thing you
can do-- so let's say

412
00:18:50,160 --> 00:18:53,840
I want to move the
test2.txt file back

413
00:18:53,840 --> 00:18:55,730
into my-- or the
test3, I guess, now,

414
00:18:55,730 --> 00:18:57,740
back into my Documents folder.

415
00:18:57,740 --> 00:19:00,020
If I go back into
my Documents folder

416
00:19:00,020 --> 00:19:03,410
with cd dot dot, which, again,
just takes me up a directory,

417
00:19:03,410 --> 00:19:10,790
I can do mv Contracts test3.

418
00:19:10,790 --> 00:19:12,690
And I'm using Tab to
autocomplete that.

419
00:19:12,690 --> 00:19:14,920
So if you ever start to
type something, use Tab.

420
00:19:14,920 --> 00:19:16,170
It'll autocomplete everything.

421
00:19:16,170 --> 00:19:17,070
It's amazing.

422
00:19:17,070 --> 00:19:22,940
So mv Contracts slash
test3.txt and then just dot.

423
00:19:22,940 --> 00:19:27,050
What that says is move
Contracts slash test3.txt,

424
00:19:27,050 --> 00:19:28,470
which is that specific file.

425
00:19:28,470 --> 00:19:31,230
That's a direct path, an
absolute path to that file.

426
00:19:31,230 --> 00:19:34,230
Move that exactly to
right here where I'm at.

427
00:19:34,230 --> 00:19:35,270
So just dot.

428
00:19:35,270 --> 00:19:38,680
It drops it right
here where I'm at.

429
00:19:38,680 --> 00:19:42,160
And now you'll see it's back
here right next to or right back

430
00:19:42,160 --> 00:19:43,170
in my Documents folder.

431
00:19:46,380 --> 00:19:49,690
Copy, similarly, so
we can copy a file.

432
00:19:49,690 --> 00:19:52,810
So let's say I want to copy
it over to the contracts.

433
00:19:52,810 --> 00:19:56,160
I can still use that same
dot syntax, as well, too.

434
00:19:56,160 --> 00:20:00,900
So if we go cd
Contracts, I can do cp.

435
00:20:00,900 --> 00:20:02,333
And now what I'm
going to do is--

436
00:20:02,333 --> 00:20:04,750
again, these are all sorts of
little shortcuts and tricks.

437
00:20:04,750 --> 00:20:06,220
I think this should work.

438
00:20:06,220 --> 00:20:11,190
Dot, dot test3 dot txt dot.

439
00:20:11,190 --> 00:20:13,090
So if we kind of
read what that says,

440
00:20:13,090 --> 00:20:16,150
that says copy from
the directory above.

441
00:20:16,150 --> 00:20:18,250
Remember, dot, dot
takes me up a directory.

442
00:20:18,250 --> 00:20:22,590
So from the directory
above, test3 dot txt.

443
00:20:22,590 --> 00:20:25,360
And then drop it right
here, exactly where I'm at.

444
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:28,530
And that's what I do with
just the single period.

445
00:20:28,530 --> 00:20:30,300
And I guess I'm
blocking this now.

446
00:20:30,300 --> 00:20:32,350
I hope I wasn't blocking
too many of these.

447
00:20:32,350 --> 00:20:34,410
I realize this in hindsight.

448
00:20:34,410 --> 00:20:35,950
So if you couldn't
see that there,

449
00:20:35,950 --> 00:20:40,110
I was putting an extra
little period after that.

450
00:20:40,110 --> 00:20:42,300
So hit Enter .

451
00:20:42,300 --> 00:20:48,370
Now ls and test3 dot txt
is in my Contracts folder,

452
00:20:48,370 --> 00:20:53,030
and it's also in my
Documents folder.

453
00:20:53,030 --> 00:20:55,110
Finally, as far as
file operations go,

454
00:20:55,110 --> 00:20:56,610
I'm going to remove this file.

455
00:20:56,610 --> 00:20:58,520
So all I have to do
to remove the file is

456
00:20:58,520 --> 00:21:03,660
do rm test3 dot
txt, and hit Enter.

457
00:21:03,660 --> 00:21:06,110
And now it's out of
my Documents folder.

458
00:21:06,110 --> 00:21:08,120
If I go into my
Contracts folder,

459
00:21:08,120 --> 00:21:10,260
though, it should
still be there.

460
00:21:10,260 --> 00:21:10,760
Right?

461
00:21:10,760 --> 00:21:12,690
Because we still have it.

462
00:21:12,690 --> 00:21:18,360
So that is the
high-level description

463
00:21:18,360 --> 00:21:24,345
of how these general
file operations go.

